WHEREAS, Coach Penny Hardaway was duly named the 2024–2025 Coach of the Year
by the AAC in recognition of his devoted instruction and success as the Head Basketball Coach
at the University of Memphis; and
WHEREAS, Coach Hardaway led the Tigers to a 26-5 overall record and a 16-2 mark in
conference play on the way to Memphis's first regular season championship in the AAC and an
AAC tournament championship as well; and
WHEREAS, the Memphis Tigers women's basketball team won its 425th game at Elma
Roane Fieldhouse on February 1, 2025; the team's lifetime record in the Fieldhouse is 426-222,
a winning percentage of .657; and
WHEREAS, the University of Memphis was one of two AAC programs to have three
1,000-point-scorers on its roster: Tilly Boler, DeeDee Hagemann, and Alasia Smith. All three
Tigers accomplished this feat during the 2024–2025 season; and
WHEREAS, the Memphis Tigers football and men's basketball teams were both ranked
in the AP Poll top twenty-five; seven Tiger football players earned First Team All-AAC honors,
and three received Third Team All-AAC honors; and
WHEREAS, the men's tennis team received an at-large bid to compete in the NCAA
Tournament; and
WHEREAS, for the third consecutive season, Memphis's women's soccer head coach
and staff were named the South Region Coaching Staff of the Year by United Soccer Coaches;
and
WHEREAS, both the Tigers men's and women's soccer teams won the AAC regular
season championship in 2024; and
WHEREAS, the University of Memphis student athletes are also successful
academically, with 94 percent of football players graduating and thirteen out of seventeen
athletic teams scoring a perfect 1000 single-year APR score; and
